If we were to make a schema for your `&lt;B&gt;` node, it would consist of a [sequence](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/dotnet/netframework-4.0/ms256089(v%3Dvs.100)) of [choice](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/dotnet/netframework-4.0/ms256109(v%3Dvs.100)) nodes, where an element of type `&lt;C&gt;`, `&lt;D&gt;`, or `&lt;B&gt;` itself might be chosen.

If we were to model this in c#, the natural way to do so would be to use a list of polymorphic objects, the items of which would correspond to the three element types. Luckily, as explained in [this answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/1643424/3744182) to *https://stackoverflow.com/q/1643139/3744182* by [Marc Gravell](https://stackoverflow.com/users/23354/marc-gravell), this scenario is supported by `XmlSerializer` by annotating the polymorphic collection with [`[XmlElement(String, Type)]`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.xml.serialization.xmlelementattribute.-ctor?view=netframework-4.8#System_Xml_Serialization_XmlElementAttribute__ctor_System_Type_) attributes, one for each concrete type that might appear in the collection.

Thus, you can define your data model as follows:

	public class BaseNode 
	{
	}

	public class B : BaseNode
	{
		[XmlElement(&quot;B&quot;, typeof(B))]
		[XmlElement(&quot;C&quot;, typeof(C))]
		[XmlElement(&quot;D&quot;, typeof(D))]
		public List&lt;BaseNode&gt; Nodes { get; } = new List&lt;BaseNode&gt;();
	}

	public class C : BaseNode
	{
		[XmlElement(ElementName=&quot;E&quot;)]
		public List&lt;string&gt; E { get; set; }
		[XmlElement(ElementName=&quot;F&quot;)]
		public List&lt;bool&gt; F { get; set; }
		[XmlElement(ElementName=&quot;G&quot;)]
		public G1 G { get; set; }
	}

	public class D : BaseNode
	{
		[XmlElement(ElementName=&quot;E&quot;)]
		public string E { get; set; }
		[XmlElement(ElementName=&quot;G&quot;)]
		public G2 G { get; set; }
	}

	public class G1
	{
		public string H { get; set; }
	}

	public class G2 
	{
		public string F { get; set; }
		public string E { get; set; }
	}

	[XmlRoot(&quot;A&quot;)]
	public class A
	{
		public B B { get; set; }
	}

Notes:

 - I made the 3 types that can appear in the `B.Nodes` collection inherit from a common ancestor `BaseNode`, so that it is not possible to add irrelevant items into the collection at runtime.  If you don&#39;t want this, you could eliminate `BaseNode` and declare your collection as a `List&lt;object&gt;`.

 - It is my experience that the various tools mentioned in *https://stackoverflow.com/q/4203540/3744182* do not always generate optimal c# classes from XML that has complex [`&lt;xsd:choice&gt;`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/dotnet/netframework-4.0/ms256109(v%3Dvs.100)) + [`&lt;xsd:sequence&gt;`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/previous-versions/dotnet/netframework-4.0/ms256089(v%3Dvs.100)) scenarios.  

   If you had a proper XSD, however, the tools from *https://stackoverflow.com/q/5217665/3744182* would generate correct c# classes.

 - In your example you have two nodes named `&lt;G&gt;` that appear to have different schemas, so I had to create two types `G1` and `G2`.

Demo fiddle [here](https://dotnetfiddle.net/QQrKTe).

